			<h3 ><a href="#p1600488">Re: Investment timing strategies for 401(k) -&gt; IRA rollovers</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1600488&amp;sid=1d86bdca4ed28121979ac6dac76b1571#p1600488"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=18281&amp;sid=1d86bdca4ed28121979ac6dac76b1571">damjam</a></strong> &raquo; Thu Jan 31, 2013 6:13 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>DaleM wrote:</cite>3. Break up the purchase into even amounts over the next several months/weeks and buy on a &quot;dollar cost averaging&quot; basis.</div></blockquote><br />Read this <a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505123_162-37843026/dollar-cost-averaging-does-it-produce-better-results/?tag=mwuser" class="postlink">article</a> by Larry Swedroe for his opinion. And this <a href="https://pressroom.vanguard.com/nonindexed/7.23.2012_Dollar-cost_Averaging.pdf" class="postlink">study</a> by Vanguard.<br />Personally I don't DCA for the reasons sited in the above links. Also I like to keep things simple.</div>

			

		</div>

		
